2026-04-21 01:32:07 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 3 positive-line wiring between input (+) and output (+) / switch connection'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that up to Control Module 2 the series chain has a normal 12 V across the + and − lines. At Control Module 3 the input (+) still measures ~12 V, but its input (−) and both output cables are at 0 V and all downstream modules see 0 V on both lines. This indicates that the 0 V reference is continuous but the + line does not pass through Module 3.\n\nInternal inspection of Module 3 reports that the negative conductor is continuous and correctly wired, and the switch itself tests nominal. However, the diagnostic found that the Control Input Cable (+) 3 has a disconnected, floating end that was originally connected to the switch. With the positive input lead floating, the internal circuit (switch, LED branch, and the output positive lead) is no longer tied to the incoming +12 V, so the module’s output positive is left at 0 V, killing the supply to all downstream modules and the load.\n\nThus, the root cause is an internal open circuit in the positive path of Control Module 3 (its input (+) lead disconnected from the switch/output path). Repairing/reconnecting this positive-line wiring in Module 3 should restore +12 V to the remainder of the chain and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
